=== Kanzan === The temple and the adjacent Atago Shrine are located at the end of the onsen street, accessible via stairs. Behind these lies the low mountain {{ill|Kanzan|ja|舘山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanzan|qq=}}, which faces [[:en:Lake Hamana|Lake Hamana]] and features a promenade with various landmarks.<ref name="sansaku">{{Cite web|ja|url=http://kanzanji.net/sansaku.html |title=Kanzan Walks |publisher=Official Website |accessdate=22 April 2021}}</ref><ref name="kanko_map">{{Cite web|ja|url=https://www.kanzanji.gr.jp/wp-content/themes/kanzanji/img/map/map_2021_spring.pdf |format=pdf |title=Kanzanji Onsen Stroll Map |publisher=[https://www.kanzanji.gr.jp/ Kanzanji Onsen Tourism Association] |accessdate=22 April 2021}}</ref> * Anadai-shi<ref name="honzon" /><ref name="sansaku" /> * Enmusubi Jizō-son<ref name="honzon" /><ref name="sansaku" /> * Sei Kannon Bosatsu (Kanzanji Great Kannon)<ref name="honzon" /><ref name="sansaku" /> * Saigyō Rock<ref name="sansaku" /> * Tosaka Rock<ref name="sansaku" /> * Fujimi Rock<ref name="sansaku" /> * Observation Deck<ref name="sansaku" />
=== Access === * '''By Car:''' 15 minutes from {{ill|Hamamatsu Nishi Interchange|ja|浜松西インターチェンジ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hamamatsu Nishi Interchange|qq=}} on the [[:en:Tōmei Expressway|Tōmei Expressway]], or closer via Kanzanji Smart Interchange.<ref name="access">{{Cite web|ja|url=http://kanzanji.net/access.html |title=Transport & Access |publisher=Official Website |accessdate=22 April 2021}}</ref> * '''By Bus:''' About 45 minutes from [[:en:Hamamatsu Station|Hamamatsu Station]] on Entetsu Bus; alight at "Kanzanji Onsen" stop and walk 5 minutes.<ref name="access" />
=== Gallery === <gallery> File:Kanzanji atagojinja 20210102.jpg|Atago Shrine within the temple grounds File:Kanzanji atagojinja torii 20210102.jpg|Atago Shrine torii. The stairs leading to Kanzanji's main hall are to the right. File:Kanzanji Seikannon Bosatsu 01.JPG|Sei Kannon Bosatsu (built in 1937<ref name="sansaku" />), likened to former Prime Minister [[:en:Shinzo Abe|Shinzō Abe]] by some media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chunichi.co.jp/article/113570 |title="Looks just like him": Abe Shinzō and Kanzanji Kannon Statue |publisher=Chunichi Shimbun |date=1 September 2020 |accessdate=6 September 2020}}</ref> </gallery>
== Kanzanji-chō == {{Pathnav|Japan|Shizuoka Prefecture|Hamamatsu City|Chūō-ku|'''Kanzanji-chō'''|hide=1|frame=1}} {{Infobox settlement | name = Kanzanji-chō | settlement_type = Town | image_skyline = Kanzanji-hotspring-town.jpg | imagesize = 300px | image_caption = Kanzanji Onsen district | image_map = | map_caption = Location of Kanzanji-chō | pushpin_map = Japan Shizuoka | latd = 34 | latm = 45 | lats = 39.69 | latNS = N | longd = 137 | longm = 36 | longs = 48.26 | longEW = E | subdivision_type = Country | subdivision_name = {{flagicon|JPN}} Japan | subdivision_type1 = Prefecture | subdivision_name1 = {{flagicon|Shizuoka Prefecture}} Shizuoka Prefecture | subdivision_type2 = City | subdivision_name2 = {{flagicon|Hamamatsu City}} Hamamatsu City | subdivision_type3 = Ward | subdivision_name3 = {{ill|Chūō-ku, Hamamatsu|ja|Chūō-ku, Hamamatsu|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūō-ku, Hamamatsu|qq=}} | established_title1 = Established | established_date1 = | area_footnotes = <ref name="menseki">{{PDFlink|[https://www.city.hamamatsu.shizuoka.jp/gyousei/library/3_tochi-kisyou/documents/27-2_menseki-jinkou_area_kubetsu.pdf Land Statistics: Neighborhood Area Sizes (March 2010) - Hamamatsu City] |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref> | area_total_km2 = 2.2506 | population_as_of = 1 December 2018 | population_footnotes = <ref name="population">{{Cite web|ja|url=https://www.city.hamamatsu.shizuoka.jp/gyousei/library/1_jinkou-setai/005_kubetsu.html |title=Population Statistics by Neighborhood |publisher=Hamamatsu City |accessdate=13 December 2018}}</ref> | population_total = 2542 | population_density_km2 = auto | timezone1 = JST | utc_offset1 = +9 | postal_code_type = Postal Code | postal_code = 431-1209<ref name="postal">{{Cite web|ja|url=https://www.post.japanpost.jp/cgi-zip/zipcode.php?zip=4311209 |title=Postal Code |publisher=Japan Post |accessdate=13 December 2018}}</ref> | area_code = 053 (Hamamatsu MA)<ref name="areacode">{{Cite web|ja|url=https://www.soumu.go.jp/main_sosiki/joho_tsusin/top/tel_number/shigai_list.html |title=List of Area Codes |publisher=Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications |accessdate=13 December 2018}}</ref> | registration_plate = Hamamatsu | footnotes = }} Located on the northeast shore of [[:en:Lake Hamana|Lake Hamana]] and featuring Uchūra Bay between Kanzanji-chō and Kusamatsu-chō, Kanzanji serves as a hub for tourism in the Hamamatsu and Lake Hamana area. The {{ill|Kanzanji Onsen Lantern Floating Fireworks Festival|ja|舘山寺温泉灯篭流し花火大会|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanzanji Onsen Lantern Floating Fireworks Festival|qq=}} is held here every summer. In 2004, the {{ill|Lake Hamana Expo|ja|浜名湖花博|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lake Hamana Expo|qq=}} was hosted in nearby Murakushi-chō, further enhancing its appeal as a tourist center.
=== Kanzanji Onsen === The {{ill|Kanzanji Onsen|ja|舘山寺温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanzanji Onsen|qq=}} was discovered in 1958 and is known for its therapeutic effects on fatigue, neuralgia, and poor circulation.
